Step-By-Step Method Details
Step-By-Step Method Details
Seeding of Cells in Imaging Dishes (Day 1)
Timing: 30 min
Cultivate cells in an imaging-compatible dish.
Detach cells from culture:
Aspirate the medium from the flask;
Add 3 mL PBS (Ca2+/Mg2+ free) to the flask and gently swirl it to remove traces of serum from the culture medium;
Aspirate the PBS from the flask;
Add 500 μL trypsin 0.5% and tilt the flask up and down and from side to side to ensure coverage of the whole flask surface;
Incubate cells at 37°C for 5 min to allow complete detachment from the flask (cells should be round and free-floating under the microscope);
Collect the detached cells:
Add 5 mL supplemented medium to the flask using a serological pipette and use that volume to gently pipette up and down along the flask surface to collect all the detached cells. Transfer the cell suspension to a 15 mL falcon tube;
Centrifuge the cells for 5 min, 400 × g at 22°C–25°C;
Discard the supernatant and gently resuspend the cells in 1 mL supplemented medium;
Count the cells in suspension using a cell counter or a Neubauer chamber.
Seed the cells in the imaging dish:
Add 2 mL supplemented medium to the imaging dish;
Add 2.5×104 cells to this dish (for an area of 35 mm - approximately 7×103 cells/cm2) and, using a 1 mL micropipette, gently aspirate up and down the cell suspension in the dish, taking care not to introduce bubbles, to avoid later clustering of attached cells;
Incubate the cells 12–16 h at 37°C (5% CO2) to allow attachment and spreading;

Bring cultures to a laminar flow hood:
If using individual dishes, use one at a time;
Remove the medium:
Aspirate the medium from the imaging dish;
Add 2 mL saline (PBS or HBSS) - add the solution gently;
Repeat at least two times;
Add 2 mL of imaging solution (see Materials and Equipment for recipe), pre-warmed.
Incubate cells with imaging solution:
Allow cells to acclimate for 5–10 min at 22°C–25°C;
Depending on the application (for instance, pre-incubation with agonists, antagonists, activators, and blockers), return the cultures to an incubator. For long-term storage, supplement the media to avoid starvation/acidification of the culture;
Take the culture dish to the microscope (the experimenter can image the cells directly from the dish, but we highly recommend not to skip steps 9–11);
Set up the microscope for image acquisition:
Turn on the temperature controller and, if adequate, CO2/O2 regulators (should be performed before - at least 30 min - incubating cells with imaging solution);
Choose the desired microscope objective and bring cells into focus (Figure 2[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig2]);
