Figure 3. Acquisition Panel with Imaging Settings (Part 2)

Carefully inspect the time series of DONOR and FRET channels for fluorescence aberrations and photobleaching; Troubleshooting[href=https://www.wicell.org#troubleshooting]
Processing – Here, we outline a completely manual downstream routine; Troubleshooting[href=https://www.wicell.org#troubleshooting]
Subtract background - DONOR and FRET channels separately:
Draw an ROI in a cell-free zone;
Measure (shortcut "m") the fluorescence;
Subtract the values from each corresponding channel (Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]B):
Go to: Process -> Math -> Subtract -> insert corresponding value;
Adjust brightness and contrast (Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]C):
Go to: Image -> Adjust -> Brightness/Contrast -> Hit “Auto” – do not hit “Apply;”
Save DONOR and FRET images as .tiff;
Mask channels:
Duplicate the entire FRET channel stack;
Threshold the desired ROI (usually a cell of interest in the field) of the duplicated FRET channel stack – (FIJI offers several auto local threshold routines):
Go to: Image -> Adjust -> Auto Local Threshold (Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]D) – 8-bit image required;
Convert the thresholded ROI into binary (white foreground – black background) image – (this step is automatic if using an auto local threshold routine) – Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]E;
Save the binary stack as .tiff and rename it to "mask;"
Generate masked 32-bit float images of DONOR and FRET channels (Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]F):
Go to: Process -> Image calculator -> choose image 1 (DONOR or FRET – repeat for both channels); image 2 (mask); operation = multiply; checkbox in create new window and in 32-bit float;
Rename to "masked DONOR," "masked FRET" and save stacks as .tiff;
Generate a ratio image (Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]G):
Go to: Process -> Image calculator -> choose image 1 (masked FRET); image 2 (masked DONOR); operation = divide; checkbox in create new window and in 32-bit float;
Convert ratio image to 16-bit (Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]H):
Go to: Image -> Type -> 16-bit, rename to “FRET-DONOR” and save as .tiff;

Apply a gradient LUT (Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]I) and adjust image contrast (Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]C);
Draw ROIs (user-defined) in cells or structures to be quantified;
Transpose ROI coordinate vectors to the ROI manager – use the shortcut "t;"
Set the measurements to be extracted form ratio images:
Go to: Analyze –> Set measurements (Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]J);
Extract quantitative measures using the "multiple measure" function of the ROI manager (Figure 6[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig6]K) – experimenter may save ROI locations for future reference;
Copy and paste values to a spreadsheet or Save as .csv for further quantitative analyses and statistics;
Display representative time series as intensity-modulated display (IMD) images (optional):
Find the IMD FRET plugin at https://doi.org/10.17632/y6z2zmsx4f.1[href=https://doi.org/10.17632/y6z2zmsx4f.1]
Download "IMDFret.txt" file;
In FIJI go to: Plugins -> Macros -> Install -> Open DONOR, FRET and intensity-modulated (IM - duplication of the brightest channel) images -> Run IMDFret plugin;
Select numerator, denominator, and IM image;
Adjust the max/min ratio (multiples of 2 are a good option) as well as the max/min intensity;
In the generated color-coded IMD stack, red-yellow represents high FRET, and blue-green represents low FRET - If required, re-adjust brightness and contrast using the sliders;
Critical: Do not skip step 16
Note: Regarding step 17a.iii. Alternatively, perform background subtraction using an average value with an in-built FIJI routine:
Go to: Process -> Subtract background -> try different values of Rolling ball radius;
Note: Regarding step 17k. If subcellular structures to be quantified are moving, it might be needed to register the FRET and DONOR channels before generating the ratio image:
Go to: Plugins -> Registration -> Register Virtual Stack Slices (https://imagej.net/Register_Virtual_Stack_Slices[href=https://imagej.net/Register_Virtual_Stack_Slices])
